<header class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro</div>
    <h1>Union Pacific (UNP)<br />Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A full discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis of North America's premier railroad franchise based on FY2025 actuals.</p>
    <div class="date">Updated: March 18, 2026</div>
  </div>
</header>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">Current Price: ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} / share</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}20; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}40`}>
      {verdictText} by {Math.abs(Number(marginOfSafety))}%
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(fcf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY25 Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Debt (Cash - Debt)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{sharesOutstanding}M</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Shares Outstanding</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>The Methodology</h2>
  <p>To value Union Pacific, we use a classic <strong>Two-Stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</strong> model. We take the exact free cash flow UNP generated in FY2025, project it out for 5 years based on a conservative growth rate, calculate a terminal value for all cash flows beyond year 5, and discount everything back to today's dollars.</p>
  <p>Finally, we subtract the company's substantial debt load and divide by the number of shares to get the per-share intrinsic value. No magic, just math.</p>

  <!-- ═══ ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h3>The 3 Core Assumptions</h3>
  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth (Yrs 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">Railroads are mature businesses. Volume growth is historically low, but pricing power allows for steady, low-to-mid single-digit cash flow growth.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">Our required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. UNP has a lower risk profile (beta ~0.9) and low cost of debt, justifying an 8% discount rate.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">The rate UNP grows forever after Year 5. Railroads move roughly inline with long-term GDP and inflation (2-3%).</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE MATH ═══ -->
  <h2>The Calculations</h2>

  <h3>1. High-Growth Phase (Years 1-5)</h3>
  <p>Starting with FY2025 FCF of <strong>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}M</strong>, growing at {(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}% per year, and discounting back at {(discountRate * 100)}%.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Year</th>
          <th>Projected FCF</th>
          <th>Discount Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>{p.year} (202{5 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}M</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(3)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}M</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of PV (Years 1-5)</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>2. Terminal Value</h3>
  <p>What is UNP worth from Year 6 to infinity? We use the Gordon Growth Model: <code>(Year 5 FCF * (1 + Terminal Rate)) / (Discount Rate - Terminal Rate)</code></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Year 6 FCF = ${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}M</li>
    <li>Terminal Value = ${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}M</li>
    <li><strong>Present Value of Terminal Value = ${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}M</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3. Final Valuation</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Years 1-5</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Plus: Cash & Equivalents</td>
          <td>${cashAndInvestments.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Less: Total Debt</td>
          <td>-${totalDebt.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Divided by Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding}M shares</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ HISTORICAL CHARTS ═══ -->
  <h2>Financial Track Record</h2>
  <p>Before trusting a forward projection, look at where the company has been. Here's Union Pacific's 5-year performance.</p>

  <h3>Revenue ($M)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {revenueHistory.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
          <div class="bar-fill revenue" style={`width: ${(r.value / 24875) * 100}%`}>
            ${(r.value / 1000).toFixed(1)}B
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h3>Free Cash Flow ($M)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {fcfHistory.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
          <div class="bar-fill fcf" style={`width: ${(r.value / 6010) * 100}%`}>
            ${(r.value / 1000).toFixed(1)}B
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h3>Earnings Per Share (Diluted)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {epsHistory.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
          <div class="bar-fill eps" style={`width: ${(r.value / 11.98) * 100}%`}>
            ${r.value.toFixed(2)}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ MARGIN TRENDS ═══ -->
  <h3>Margin Trends</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>Operating Margin</th>
          <th>Profit Margin</th>
          <th>FCF Margin</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {marginHistory.map(m => (
          <tr>
            <td>{m.year}</td>
            <td>{m.operating}%</td>
            <td>{m.profit}%</td>
            <td>{m.fcfMargin}%</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> Operating margins are structurally high, a hallmark of Class I railroads operating as regional duopolies. FCF margins remain consistently above 20%, though cap-ex needs are significant to maintain the track network.</p>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses 5% growth and an 8% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions. Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Since Union Pacific is heavily indebted and capital intensive, the intrinsic value is highly sensitive to the discount rate and required capital returns.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power:</strong> Railroads have historically been able to raise prices above inflation. Stronger pricing realization could push FCF growth closer to 7-8%.</li>
    <li><strong>Operating Efficiency:</strong> Further improvements in Precision Scheduled Railroading (PSR) could decrease operating ratios and boost margins further.</li>
    <li><strong>Onshoring/Nearshoring:</strong> Increased manufacturing in Mexico and the US could drive structural volume growth on UNP's network over the next decade.</li>
    <li><strong>Share Buybacks:</strong> UNP returns significant capital to shareholders via buybacks, increasing per-share value over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Downturns:</strong> Railroad volumes are highly sensitive to industrial production and consumer goods imports. A severe recession could severely contract FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulation:</strong> The Surface Transportation Board (STB) could impose pricing caps or force reciprocal switching, eating into margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Labor Costs:</strong> Heavily unionized workforce; future contract negotiations could drive up operating costs faster than inflation.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With over $32 billion in debt, higher interest rates upon refinancing will increase interest expense and reduce cash flows to equity.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">UNP is a wide-moat, highly stable infrastructure asset operating as a duopoly in the Western US. It has a low beta (~0.9) and predictable cash flows. In a 4.18% 10-year Treasury environment, an 8% WACC reflects its stability relative to the broader market.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is UNP's debt load so high?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Railroads are immensely capital-intensive. They own their tracks, locomotives, and terminals. This asset-heavy model allows them to carry higher debt loads safely compared to asset-light tech or services companies.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why assume only 5% FCF growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Railroad overall volume growth has been stagnant to negative over the last decade (e.g., coal secular decline). Growth comes almost entirely from pricing power and efficiency gains. 5% is a realistic long-term assumption for a mature industrial company.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

